    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Before data can be opened in the specXplore dashboard, it needs to be processed using the specXplore importing pipeline. The processing workflows and intermediate data structures used by specXplore are built upon a cohort of open-source software Python data science packages, namely, matchms, MS2Query, ms2deepscore, spec2vec, kmedoids, Cython, numpy, pandas, scikit-learn, and scipy. The input data for specXplore spectral data exploration are MS/MS spectral data. LC\u2013MS/MS data preprocessing (i.e., feature detection and MS/MS spectral exporting) is assumed to have been done elsewhere, e.g., using MZMine3, in order to reduce data set size and feature redundancy. The MS/MS feature data are assumed to be in .mgf (mascot generic format) format, where each entry should have a unique feature identifier, a precursor mass to charge ratio, and spectral data in the form of one or more mass to charge ratio and intensity value tuples. Spectral data are imported into Python using matchms, and basic specXplore data processing is performed. Spectral data can then be used to initialize a template specXplore object that automatically computes pairwise spectral similarities using three similarity scores: ms2deepscore, modified cosine scores, and spec2vec scores.",
      "asbval:note": "The research question is directly addressed in the paper's Materials and Methods section, which describes the importing pipeline architecture and input format (.mgf) for creating a specXplore session object.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-3c04444",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "What is the input format and processing pipeline architecture for converting raw LC-MS/MS spectral data into a serialized specXplore session data object in the importing stage?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:53:18.066807+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Spectral data can then be used to initialize a template specXplore object that automatically computes pairwise spectral similarities using three similarity scores: ms2deepscore, modified cosine scores, and spec2vec scores. For the machine learning scores, pretrained models provided with MS2Query are used. The central overview of specXplore is based on a t-SNE embedding of the ms2deepscore pairwise similarity matrix serving as the primary similarity score.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes initialization of a specXplore object from spectral data. While the paper does not explicitly state 'serialized file saved to disk', it describes the creation of a specXplore session object that is subsequently loaded into the dashboard ('Upon opening the app and loading the data'), implying persistence/serialization.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-3c04444",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Serialized specXplore session data object file saved to disk",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:53:18.066807+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The specXplore workflow is divided into a Python data importing pipeline and a visual analysis dashboard using dash. The processing workflows and intermediate data structures used by specXplore are built upon a cohort of open-source software Python data science packages, namely, matchms, MS2Query, ms2deepscore, spec2vec, kmedoids, Cython, numpy, pandas, scikit-learn, and scipy.",
      "asbval:note": "Python is explicitly stated as the language for the importing pipeline.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-3c04444",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Python",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:53:18.066807+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For the wheat data set, the pipeline preprocessing time was less than 15 min (on a MacBook Pro laptop with Apple M1 Pro processor 2021), most of which was spent on local library search via MS2Query. Using the same system, the processing time for the larger urine data set was less than 75 min, whereof approximately 62 min was taken up by MS2Query and 9 min for all pairwise spectral similarity computations. Spectral data from .mgf files was loaded into the preprocessing jupyter notebooks and processed into a specXplore session object (see illustrative example notebooks https://github.com/kevinmildau/specxplore-illustrative-examples).",
      "asbval:note": "Jupyter notebooks are explicitly mentioned as the tool used for preprocessing and loading spectral data into the specXplore session object.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-3c04444",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Jupyter notebooks",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:53:18.066807+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The card focuses narrowly on the importing pipeline and session object creation, which is a legitimate subtask of the broader specXplore workflow described in the paper. The paper's primary focus is on the interactive dashboard and exploratory data analysis, but the importing pipeline is well-documented in the Materials and Methods section.",
        "The card does not mention the specific Python packages (matchms, MS2Query, ms2deepscore, spec2vec, etc.) that are central to the importing pipeline, though these are extensively documented in the paper."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 2,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:53:18.066807+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
